You need to use `Map` that will have the ID as its key, and the value as a `List` of your object. Suppose you have the following class:

```java
class Item {
  
  private int id;
  private String name;

  public Item(int id, String name) {
    this.id = id;
    this.name = name;
  }
   
  public int getId() { return this.id; }
}
```

Your result should be of type `Map&lt;Integer, List&lt;Item&gt;&gt;`. One way to achieve this is by using [`Collectors.groupingBy`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/stream/Collectors.html#groupingBy-java.util.function.Function-). For example:

    list.stream().collect(Collectors.groupingBy(Item::getId));

This will create a map, that&#39;s grouped by the `id` property of the `Item` class.

