answers.body_markdown:
In order to use the [range-based for loop](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/range-for) in your user-defined types, you need to define `begin()` and `end()` iterators. That means, `Machine` needs to have the following member functions which return the iterator of the member container. **([See live online](https://wandbox.org/permlink/1gKTZ4YhrZyySPdA))**

    struct Machine
    {
    	vector&lt;Item&gt; menu;
    	auto begin() { return menu.begin(); } // auto return requires C++14
    	auto end()   { return menu.end();   }
        
        // or in C++11, you provide the correct return type
        // decltype(menu.begin()) begin() { return menu.begin(); }
	    // decltype(menu.end())   end()   { return menu.end();   }
    };


----------


Otherwise, you need to provide the iterative object directly to the loop. That means, in your case, in order to work with a minimal change:

    void test(Machine const&amp; machine) // pass by `const-ref` as the machine is read-only inside the function
    {
    	for (const Item&amp; i : machine.menu) { // const&amp; : same reason as above ^^
        //                   ^^^^^^^^^^^^ --&gt; std::vector has iterators: begin(), end() 
    		cout &lt;&lt; &quot;item = &quot; &lt;&lt; i.name;
    	}
    }


----------

Some other notes:

 - The `initItem` function is not the way you do in normally in C++ (or any other object-oriented programming languages). That is the job of a [constructor](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/initializer_list). In order to change the value of the member(s) in an object, the setter (member) function will be used. A good starting would be:
    ```c++
    class Item
    {
    private:
    	std::string name;
    	double price;
    	unsigned int quantity;
    	unsigned int amountInCart;
    	bool addedToCart;
    
    public:
    	// constructor
    	Item(std::string name, double price, unsigned int quantity,
    		unsigned int amountInCart, bool addedToCart)
    		: name{ name } // or name{ std::move(name) } when you learn about the move-semantics
    		, price{ price}
    		, quantity{ quantity }
    		, amountInCart{ amountInCart }
    		, addedToCart{ addedToCart }
    	{}
    	// ... getter and setter functions
    };
    ```
   You create an object now like: 
    ```c++
    Item cake{ &quot;Cake&quot;, 3.00, 5, 0, false };
    ```
 - Please do not practice with `using namespace std;`. See here for more: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/1452721/why-is-using-namespace-std-considered-bad-practice
 - I have passed the `Machine` object to the function `test`(also in range based loop, `Item` objects) passed by `const` qualified referance. Whenver, the data is non-modifiable under the any scopes, you should pass the parameters like that, so that unwanted copying can be avoided(*creadits @Klaus*): . For further readings: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/270408/is-it-better-in-c-to-pass-by-value-or-pass-by-constant-reference

